Given these reasons, I will oppose Director Pompeo’s nomination in the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on Monday.

Finally, Director Pompeo’s past statements as a Congressman and candidate on a range of issues give me great concern since the role of Secretary of State is in part to speak for all Americans on issues of our shared values to rest of the world.

However, I remain concerned that Dir Pompeo won’t challenge the President in critical moments. On vital decisions facing our country, Dir Pompeo seems less concerned with rule of law & partnership with our allies & more inclined to emphasize unilateral action & the use of force
He is also knowledgeable and clear-eyed about the diplomatic and security challenges we face around the world.

I do not make this decision without reservations.  I am convinced Dir Pompeo would be a strong advocate for the career professionals of the State Dept and that he would repair some of the damage that vacancies and budget uncertainties have created over the past eighteen months.

While I respect his background of military and public service and am encouraged by his stated commitment to our diplomatic corps, I remain concerned that Director Pompeo will embolden, rather than moderate or restrain, President Trump’s most belligerent and dangerous instincts.
After careful consideration, I have decided that I will oppose CIA Director Mike Pompeo’s nomination to become Secretary of State.

full_text: This is a significant step forward, and it’s one example of how, when we work across the aisle and keep pushing forward – we can make a real difference for American families.
Our bill was enacted into law in late December & this week, the Trump Admin announced that they will put our policy into action: https://t.co/Cn8ZnCAvBg
It was a pretty simple piece of legislation, with a minimal cost, but a significant impact for families already dealing with the unthinkable.

So, a few years ago, @senrobportman, @SenAngusKing & I introduced the Stop Taxing Death and Disability Act that would eliminate that unfair tax penalty levied on student loans forgiven to these families.
We looked into this and found out that thousands of families across the country were experiencing the same issue after having a loved one pass away or become permanently disabled.
To put it simply: by fixing one problem for a family in need, the government ended up creating a new problem for the family.

The Department of Education forgave the loans, but there was a catch. The IRS then counted those forgiven loans as income, meaning the family, still grieving, suddenly had a significantly higher tax bill.
It all started when I heard from a constituent who was grieving the death of a loved one who had outstanding student loans when they passed away.
There are plenty of examples of things *not* working in our politics and our government at the moment, but I want to share a success story…

As always, I remain willing to work across the aisle to pass a real, bipartisan tax reform bill for the middle class, but our opportunity to do that is quickly slipping away.
This process isn't finished yet, as the Senate and House bills remain very different, but I am very concerned that we're close to making our already-broken tax code even worse.
It was written with no meaningful consultation between the two parties and it is highly unpopular with the American public, for good reason.

The bill that appears likely to pass the Senate soon is a bad one. There's no sugar coating it. It gives away tens of billions in corporate tax cuts with no strings attached, hurts the middle class over the long run, guts the ACA, & adds more than $1 trillion to the national debt

Over the last few days, I've been working with a handful of my Republican & Democratic colleagues to try to find a way - any way - to stop this backroom, partisan process & force both parties to work together. We got close to an agreement, but ultimately didn't succeed.

For months, I've urged my Republican colleagues to work across the aisle on a bipartisan tax reform bill that Senators from both parties could get behind. 

Last week, I joined more than a dozen Dem Senators to ask our GOP colleagues to slow this process down and work together.
